The abolition of slavery with the 13th Amendment in 1865 was a pivotal moment in United States history. This event still impacts society today in various ways. The legacy of slavery has contributed to ongoing racial disparities and tensions. The civil rights movement of the 1950s and 1960s, affirmative action policies, and the Black Lives Matter movement can all be seen as responses to the long-term effects of slavery. Additionally, the economic and social structures that were built during the era of slavery have had lasting effects on the distribution of wealth and opportunities.
